[llm] Cleaned response: {"questions":[{"q":"A company decides to promote from within rather than hiring externally. This leads to quicker integration but may limit diversity in ideas. Which assessment best captures this approach?","o":["Promoting internally can enhance motivation but might restrict fresh perspectives.","Hiring externally guarantees a wider range of ideas but increases onboarding time.","Promoting internally is less risky since existing employees are already familiar with the culture.","Both approaches equally affect employee morale and innovation."],"a":"A","question_type":"case_based","concept_id":"business_studies::staffing","trap_option":"C","strong_distractors":["B","D"],"why_not_textbook":"The focus is on evaluating strategic staffing choices rather than definitions.","why_cuet_level":"Requires understanding of implications of staffing strategies.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"This option correctly identifies the trade-off between internal promotion and idea diversity.","B":"Although it mentions external hiring, it misunderstands the impact on onboarding time as a guarantee.","C":"This option incorrectly assumes that familiarity negates all risks associated with internal promotion.","D":"This suggests equal effects without considering the distinct nature of each approach."}},{"q":"Statement I: Internal recruitment enhances employee loyalty. Statement II: External recruitment provides new skills and perspectives. Which evaluation correctly reflects these statements?","o":["Both statements are valid, highlighting different benefits of recruitment methods.","Only Statement I is valid, as external recruitment does not contribute to loyalty.","Only Statement II is valid because internal recruitment limits skills development.","Both statements are invalid since neither method impacts employee engagement."],"a":"A","question_type":"statement_based","concept_id":"business_studies::staffing","trap_option":"B","strong_distractors":["C","D"],"why_not_textbook":"The question focuses on evaluating the implications of recruitment methods instead of definitions.","why_cuet_level":"Encourages critical thinking about recruitment strategies' impact.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"Both statements accurately reflect the benefits of their respective recruitment methods.","B":"This option wrongly dismisses external recruitment's contributions to loyalty and engagement.","C":"This claim inaccurately limits the scope of internal recruitment's benefits to loyalty alone.","D":"This option incorrectly negates both statements, overlooking their valid points."}},{"q":"A manager believes that hiring externally will always bring innovative ideas. However, they notice a lack of cultural fit among new recruits. What does this scenario highlight?","o":["External hiring can enrich innovation but may lead to integration challenges within teams.","Cultural fit is irrelevant when prioritizing innovation through external hires.","Innovation from external hires guarantees long-term success in all cases.","Internal candidates are always a better choice for maintaining team cohesion."],"a":"A","question_type":"application_based","concept_id":"business_studies::staffing","trap_option":"C","strong_distractors":["B","D"],"why_not_textbook":"The focus is on analyzing real-world implications rather than textbook definitions.","why_cuet_level":"Encourages evaluation of practical outcomes of staffing decisions.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"This option correctly identifies the balance needed between innovation and cultural fit.","B":"This statement incorrectly asserts that cultural fit has no importance in hiring decisions.","C":"This claim inaccurately presents external hiring as a guaranteed solution without acknowledging potential issues.","D":"This option wrongly suggests that internal candidates are superior without considering context."}},{"q":"Statement I: Hiring from outside can rejuvenate a team. Statement II: Relying solely on internal promotions can lead to stagnation. Which option best evaluates these statements?","o":["Both statements are valid, recognizing the need for balance in staffing strategies.","Only Statement I is valid, as internal promotions do not affect team dynamics significantly.","Only Statement II is valid since external hires do not guarantee rejuvenation of teams.","Both statements are invalid because all teams benefit equally from either approach."],"a":"A","question_type":"comparison_based","concept_id":"business_studies::staffing","trap_option":"D","strong_distractors":["B","C"],"why_not_textbook":"The question emphasizes critical evaluation rather than rote learning of concepts.","why_cuet_level":"Encourages understanding of the dynamics between staffing strategies.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"Both statements highlight important aspects of staffing that need consideration for effective management.","B":"This option incorrectly minimizes the impact that internal promotions can have on team dynamics and growth.","C":"This statement fails to recognize that external hires could also lead to stagnation if not managed well.","D":"This option erroneously dismisses both claims without acknowledging their validity."}},{"q":"In a recent analysis, a firm found that promoting existing staff reduced turnover but limited access to new skills. How does this scenario reflect on their staffing strategy?","o":["Promoting from within fosters loyalty but may narrow skill diversity in the organization.","Hiring externally always ensures skill enhancement regardless of retention rates.","Maintaining a high turnover rate improves overall team performance in the long run.","Internal promotions are more effective in boosting innovation compared to external hires."],"a":"A","question_type":"case_based","concept_id":"business_studies::staffing","trap_option":"C","strong_distractors":["B","D"],"why_not_textbook":"The focus is on analyzing outcomes rather than simply recalling definitions or concepts.","why_cuet_level":"Requires application of concepts to evaluate staffing outcomes critically.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"This option correctly identifies the trade-off between retention and skill diversity in staffing strategy.","B":"This claim inaccurately presents external hiring as an absolute solution for skill enhancement without context.","C":"This statement wrongly assumes turnover improves performance universally, ignoring potential downsides.","D":"This option incorrectly equates internal promotions with higher innovation without evidence."}}]}
